  "nursesNote": "Delirium is a sudden, fluctuating confusion that is usually reversible and signals an underlying problem (infection, medications, dehydration, low oxygen), so the nurse looks for and treats the cause. Dementia (such as Alzheimer's) is a gradual, chronic, progressive decline that is not reversible, with recent memory lost first. For both, the nurse keeps the patient safe (fall and wandering risk), uses simple, calm, one-step communication, reorients or redirects, and provides a consistent routine with low stimulation. Restraints and overstimulation are avoided; confusion that worsens in the evening (sundowning) is eased with light and reassurance.",
  "providerOrders": [
    "Identify and treat the cause of delirium",
    "Keep the patient safe from falls and wandering",
    "Use simple, calm, one-step communication and reorient",
    "Provide a consistent routine with low stimulation",
    "Avoid restraints and overstimulation"
  ],
